{
  "texts": [
    "While autonomous AI can provide diagnostic insights in the absence of skilled radiologists, decisions made by AI systems could potentially lack nuanced human judgment.",
    "Striking a balance between accessible healthcare and maintaining diagnostic quality becomes a critical ethical concern.Ultimately, the successful implementation of AI in radiology relies on an understanding of its implications, and proactive measures, including radiologist education, AI explainability, and radiologist-AI accuracy monitoring to address safety and ethical concerns.",
    "Section 9: ConclusionArtificial intelligence in radiology is here to stay.",
    "It has the potential to add significant value to our care for patients, and to expand the horizons of what imaging can offer.",
    "Radiomics, for example, is an expanding field of data extraction and analysis that could not exist without AI.As this exciting new technology increases its penetration and impact in healthcare, it is vital that it do so in a manner that is safe, and directed entirely towards benefit."
  ]
}